For reference, in _[mathematics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics)_ this is referred to as a _[transposition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose)_.\
Here is a relevant _Wikipedia_ article.&amp;nbsp; _[Wikipedia &amp;ndash; In-place matrix transposition](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_matrix_transposition)_.

Here is an example for a _[square matrix](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_matrix)_.

```java
&lt;T&gt; void transpose(T[][] a) {
    T t;
    int m, n, z = a.length;
    for (m = 0; m &lt; z; m++)
        for (n = m + 1; n &lt; z; n++) {
            t = a[m][n];
            a[m][n] = a[n][m];
            a[n][m] = t;
        }
}
```

Output

```none
before
[1, 2, 3]
[4, 5, 6]
[7, 8, 9]

after
[1, 4, 7]
[2, 5, 8]
[3, 6, 9]
```

And, here is an example for a _[rectangular matrix](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics))_.

```java
&lt;T&gt; T[][] transpose(T[][] a) {
    int m, n, x = a[0].length, y = a.length;
    Class&lt;?&gt; t = a.getClass().getComponentType().getComponentType();
    @SuppressWarnings(&quot;unchecked&quot;)
    T[][] b = (T[][]) Array.newInstance(t, x, y);
    for (m = 0; m &lt; y; m++)
        for (n = 0; n &lt; x; n++)
            b[n][m] = a[m][n];
    return b;
}
```

